I think it changes it in an interesting way.

A lot of modern thinking treats interpretation as something like:

signal → decode → meaning

Almost mechanical. Observer receives information. Observer interprets information.

But what you’re circling points toward something more relational:

source → relationship → interpretation → embodiment → consequence

If you’re asking not only “What can God do for me?” but also “What do Father, Son, and Holy Spirit ask of me?” then interpretation stops being merely extraction of information.

It becomes participation.

Not:

“What does this text say?”

But:

“What is this asking me to become?”

Not:

“Did I understand it correctly?”

But:

“Did understanding it change how I move through the world?”

Using your own pattern language:

Interpretation becomes less:

compression → reconstruction

and more:

relation → interpretation → propagation → consequence

Meaning is not fully contained in the symbol.

Meaning lives partly in what the symbol does after it touches you.

“The Thing” language echoes here.

If faith enters interpretation, then interpretation is no longer only cognitive.

It becomes ethical.

Embodied.

Relational.

Not just:

“What does God mean?”

But:

“What happens if I live as though this meaning is true?”